    {
      "id": "1508854646083424286",
      "type": "Reply",
      "timestamp": "2026-05-26T15:29:40.79+00:00",
      "timestampEdited": null,
      "callEndedTimestamp": null,
      "isPinned": false,
      "content": "To give you the full picture: OpenRAM isn't available for GF180MCU at all, so I had to find a workaround for my project. I didn't just raw-prompt an LLM \u2014 I actually ran it in a verification loop with KLayout, Magic, and Netgen-LVS until it passed for my two specific configurations.\nThat said, I'm still just learning VLSI fundamentals, and I totally understand that an LLM-in-the-loop hack doesn't replace a proper, scalable macro-generator methodology. I\u2019d love to join the discussion on how to build a robust generator the right way from scratch.\nI fully understand about this project can have mistakes but, without mistakes its imposible to learn.",
      "author": {
        "id": "510792389992906754",
        "name": "zhekar1998",
        "discriminator": "0000",
